The async.send method wasn't really doing anything useful. It was just calling the r.send() method of the Request object 'r'. It took an optional kwarg pools, and assigned it to r._pools which isn't used by anything. This situation was eaither broken or not fully implemented yet. I modified async.map to call r.send rather than send(r) and then modified async.send to actually make use of the pool that it is passed.

Fixed URI re-encoding on Python 3 (Issue #369).Request.full_url now performs requoting of the path (like it does in Python 2).nRequest.path_url no longer quotes the already-quoted path (double quoting).nFixed utils.requote_path so it works properly in Python 3.n
Added test case for Issue #369.Tests that legal reserved and unreserved characters in the path are notnpercent-encoded. Currently fails.n
Added test case testing URI normalisation.Tests that percent-encoded unreserved characters get de-encoded.n
Changed test case test_path_is_not_double_encoded.Uses the space character instead of ~ as a test (since ~ is unreserved, itnshouldn't really be encoded at all).n

Fixed URI encoding of reserved characters (Issue #369).Previously, util.requote_path would unquote and requote all characters,ncausing reserved characters to become encoded (changing the semantics of thenURI). Now, it has special code for unquoting just the unreserved characters,nthen quotes only illegal characters.nThis ensures that illegal characters are fixed, and URIs are normalised, butnreserved characters do not erroneously become quoted.nTest case test_session_with_escaped_url now passes.n
Simplify requote_path.It no longer needs to split on '/' since '/' will not be encoded.n

Lazily encode data, params, filesPreviously, data, params, and files were encoded and stored innRequest.__init__, and subsequently put into service duringnRequest.send. The problem with this approach is that hooks and authncallables need to be aware of the eager encoding, and if they touch thenoriginals, make sure to update the encoded versions.nnA better approach is to only encode late in the sending process. Thisnway, hooks and auth callables can safely make changes without fear ofnthe old, encoded variant overriding it.n

Add the ability to turn off HTTP 0.9 support.While debugging an issue I discovered requests was coming back with 200nresponse, when it really shouldn't have.  It turns out this happened forntwo reasons: the jetty server running the app was rather lame andndidn't fail the request as a Bad Request, and httplib was happy to letnmalformed data through and call it success.nnIt turns out httplib's strict flag controls this behavior of whether ornnot to validate the status line.  The underlying urllib3 supports thenconcept as well.  There was a bug there to that is now fixed upstream.nnThe last step is exposing this through requests.  This introduces ansupports_http0.9 flag to help control this behavior.  It defaults tonto True to preserve the current behavior.   Setting it to False willnallow the underlying HTTPConnection to validate the status line.n

Rewrite CaseInsensitiveDict to work correctly/sanelyFixes #649 and #1329 by making Session.headers a CaseInsensitiveDict,nand fixing the implementation of CID. Credit for the brilliant ideanto map `lowercased_key -> (cased_key, mapped_value)` goes ton@gazpachoking, thanks a bunch.nnChanges from original implementation of CaseInsensitiveDict:nn1.  CID is rewritten as a subclass of `collections.MutableMapping`.n2.  CID remembers the case of the last-set key, but `__setitem__`nand `__delitem__` will handle keys without respect to case.n3.  CID returns the key case as remembered for the `keys`, `items`,nand `__iter__` methods.n4.  Query operations (`__getitem__` and `__contains__`) are done inna case-insensitive manner: `cid['foo']` and `cid['FOO']` willnreturn the same value.n5.  The constructor as well as `update` and `__eq__` have undefinednbehavior when given multiple keys that have the same `lower()`.n6.  The new method `lower_items` is like `iteritems`, but keys arenall lowercased.n7.  CID raises `KeyError` for `__getitem__` as normal dicts do. Thenold implementation returnedn6.  The `__repr__` now makes it obvious that it's not a normal dict.nnSee PR #1333 for the discussions that lead up to this implementationn

quote qop options in Digest AuthBased on RFC2617 (http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2617), the value ofn'qop-options' directive should be quoted with double quotes:nnqop-optionsn This directive is optional, but is made so only for backwardn compatibility with RFC 2069 [6]; it SHOULD be used by alln implementations compliant with this version of the Digestn scheme. If present, it is a quoted string of one or moren tokens indicating the quality of protection values supported byn the server.  The value auth indicates authentication; then value auth-int indicates authentication withn integrity protection; see thenncurl comamnd-line tool also appends these quotes. You can see thisnby `curl -v --digest --user user:passwd http://example.com/digest-auth`.nUnfortunately, some minor server-side implementations seem to be sensitivenon this difference.n

Use buffering for HTTP responses on chunked requestsFor non-chunked requests, the request is performed using the 'urlopen'nmethod that underlying uses buffering for the HTTP responses (for Pythonn2.7+ versions). Flip conditional in session.send()Previously we checked that the `request` being sent was an instance of anPreparedRequest. If a user somehow created a PreparedRequest using a differentnRequests library instance, this check makes the request un-sendable.nn(This happened recently - unbeknownst to me, my server was running an outdatednversion of pip, vulnerable to this issue - pypa/pip#1489, which createsnmultiple subdirectories (src/requests, src/requests/requests) when you rerunnpip install --target. So the PreparedRequest was being created in one versionnof the library and compared against the other version of the library, andnthrowing this exception, even though they were both PreparedRequest instances!)nnIt would probably be preferable to check the object's behavior (instead ofnits type), but a PreparedRequest has a lot of behavior, and it wouldn't benreally feasible or allow us to provide a helpful error message to check allnof it here. Instead flip the conditional to guard against the user sending annunprepared Request, which should still give us most of the benefits of thenbetter error message.nnFixes #3102n

Add documentation for available status codesThere was no way to determine what actual names were available outsidenof looking at the source code. They were not listed in the documentationnor accessible through the interactive help.nnIn addition, doing `pydoc requests.status_codes` displayed some prettynunhelpful information - the utf-8 encoding string was included in thenmodule name, there was no description, and internal variables used forninitialisation leaked into the module scope:nnDATAncode = 511ncodes = <lookup 'status_codes'>ntitle = 'network_authentication'ntitles = ('network_authentication_required', 'network_auth', ...nnThis change prevents the internal variables from leaking, adds andocstring (which has the side-effect of correcting the module name), andnappends information on the allowed status code names to the docstringnwhen the module is initialised.nnThe improved module documentation is then used in the API documentationnto provide another easy reference to the complete list of status codes.n
